  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="review-functions-2">
    <title>Using Functions</title>
    
    <remark>
      <title>
        Function Notation: Functions of a Single Variable
      </title>  
      <p>
        The notation <m>f(x)</m> has two pieces: an input and a rule. We are applying the <em>rule</em> <m>f</m> to the <em>input</em> <m>x</m>. The result is an output, usually denoted <m>y</m>. So we can write
        <me>
          y = f(x)
        </me>
        as a way to say <q>the output <m>y</m> is the result of applying the rule <m>f</m> to the input <m>x</m></q>. This should be read as <q><m>y</m> equals <m>f</m> of <m>x</m></q>
      </p>
    </remark>

    <remark>
      <title>Evaluating Functions</title>
      <p>
        To evaluate a function <m>f(x)</m>, replace all instances of the variable <m>x</m> with the input shown.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x) = x^2 + 5</m>. Evaluate the following:
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(1)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(0)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(-2)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(a)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(x + h)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(1)=6</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(0)=5</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(-2)=9</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(a)=a^2+5</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(x + h)=x^2+2xh+h^2+5</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the following function rules: <m>f(x) = x-1, g(x) = -x^2, h(x) = 2^x</m>. Write the function notation for the descriptions given, then compute.
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f</m> applied to the input 5
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>g</m> applied to the input <m>a + 1</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>h</m> applied to the input <m>3 + r</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(5) = 4</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>g(a+1)=-a^2-2ah-h^2</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>h(3+r) = 2^{3+r} = 8\cdot 2^r</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="review-functions-3">
    <title>Combining Functions</title>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Function Combinations</title>
      <tabular>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell>
            Name
          </cell>
          <cell>
            Notation
          </cell>
          <cell>
            Translation
          </cell>
          <cell>
            Note
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>
            Sum
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>
              (f+g)(x)
            </m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>
              f(x) + g(x)
            </m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>
            Difference
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>
              (f-g)(x)
            </m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>
              f(x) - g(x)
            </m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>
            Product
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>
              (f\cdot g)(x)
            </m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>
              f(x)\cdot g(x)
            </m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>(f\cdot g)</m> can be written as <m>(fg)</m> as well
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>
            Quotient
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>\lrpar{\dfrac{f}{g}}(x)</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>
              \dfrac{f(x)}{g(x)}
            </m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>g(x)</m> cannot be zero
          </cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </assemblage>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x) = 3x-1</m> and <m>g(x) = x^2+x+1</m>. Write and simplify the following.
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (f+g)(x)
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (f-g)(x)
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (fg)(x)
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \lrpar{\dfrac{f}{g}}(x)
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (f+g)(x) = x^2 + 4x
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (f-g)(x) = -x^2 + 2x - 2
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (fg)(x) = 3x^3+2x^2+x-1
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \lrpar{\dfrac{f}{g}}(x) = \dfrac{3x-1}{x^2+x-1}
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        Functions can also be combined using <em>composition</em>: using one function as an input to another. The notation is given by
        <me>
          (f\circ g)(x) = f(g(x))
        </me>
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x) = 3x-1</m> and <m>g(x) = x^2+x+1</m>. Write and simplify the following.
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (f\circ g)(x)
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (g\circ f)(x)
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  g(-4x)
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  f(g(-x))
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (f\circ g)(x)= 3x^2+3x+2
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  (g\circ f)(x)=9x^2-3x+1
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  g(-4x)=-12x-1
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  f(g(-x))=3x^2-3x+2
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        Given two functions <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m>, the composition <m>(f\circ g)(x)</m> has the domain
        <me>
          \text{Dom}\,(f\circ g) = \lrbrace{x\mid x\in \text{Dom}\,(g)\text{ and }g(x)\in\text{Dom}\, (f)}
        </me>
        and the range
        <me>
          \text{Range}\, (f\circ g) = \lrbrace{y=f(x)\mid x\in \text{Range}\, (g)}
        </me>
      </p>
    </remark>

