  <subsection xml:id="review-functions-4">
    <title>Symmetry</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-even-odd">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A function <m>f(x)</m> is said to be <term>even</term><idx><h>even function</h></idx> if it has the property that
          <me>
            f(-x) = f(x)
          </me>
          for all <m>x</m> in its domain.
        </p>
        <p>
          A function <m>g(x)</m> is said to be <term>odd</term><idx><h>odd function</h></idx> if it has the property that
          <me>
            g(-x) = -g(x)
          </me>
          for all <m>x</m> in its domain.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine if the following functions are even, odd, or neither.
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  f(x) = x^7 + x^5 -x
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  g(x) = 3-x^2
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  h(x) = x^2-x^3
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Odd
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Even
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Neither
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="review-functions-5">
    <title>Transformations of Functions</title>
    
    <assemblage>
      <title>Vertical and Horizontal Shifts</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>c\gt 0</m>. To obtain the graph of 
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y = f(x) + c</m>, shift the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m>  up by <m>c</m> units
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y = f(x) - c</m>, shift the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> down by <m>c</m> units
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y = f(x+c)</m>, shift the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> left by <m>c</m> units
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y = f(x-c)</m>, shift the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> right by <m>c</m> units
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Vertical and Horizontal Stretching/Reflecting</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>c \gt 1</m>. To obtain the graph of 
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y = c\cdot f(x)</m>, stretch the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> vertically by a factor of <m>c</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y=\lrpar{\dfrac{1}{c}}\cdot f(x)</m>, shrink the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> vertically by a factor of <m>c</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y= f(c\cdot x)</m>, shrink the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> horizontally by a factor of <m>c</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y = f\lrpar{\dfrac{1}{c}\cdot x}</m>, stretch the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> horizontally by a factor of <m>c</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y=-f(x)</m>, reflect the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> about the <m>x-</m>axis
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y=f(-x)</m>, reflect the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> about the <m>y-</m>axis
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>g(1) = 3</m>, what point must be on the graph of <m>h(t) = -2g(t-1)+6</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\lrpar{2,0}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>